The paper deals with Approximate Message Passing (AMP) algorithms, which are commonly used in compressed sensing reconstruction, robust regression, Bayesian estimation, low-rank matrix recovery, phase retrieval, and community detection in graphs. These applications are typically studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT), Machine Learning (cs.LG), Multimedia (cs.MM), Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), and Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-categories of arXiv CS. The paper specifically focuses on the state evolution of AMP with non-separable functions, which is a theoretical analysis of the algorithm's performance. This analysis is likely to be of interest to researchers in the above-mentioned sub-categories, hence the paper is likely to belong to these sub-categories.
